@node "GUIIntro" "SD GUI Interface Intro"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}Introduction - why this GUI ?@{ub}@{fg text}

 This  graphical  user  interface  was born many years ago, when there were no
 alternatives,  there  was  no MUI, no ClassAct, nor the others. To be honest,
 neither  GadTools  had been born yet... those were the times of 1.3. Tired of
 the classical Intuition look I started writing a more friendly interface.
 The  most  beautiful  thing  was  the  possibility of customizing the various
 parameters,  so  I  also wrote an editor which allowed to fully configure the
 environment of a program with few clicks.

 So the first configurable interface was born, even if nobody ever noticed it.
 Then,  as  time  passed,  my  urge  of adding something new grew bigger, also
 because the operating system itself experienced some evolution. But from that
 moment  many  alternatives  have  been born, many programmers started writing
 graphical  user  interfaces  for every purpose, some Freeware, some Shareware
 (and expensive, too).

 So  I looked around and I tried to make my mind up. The possible choices were
 only  two:  using the system interface or try to slightly modernize the one I
 had  already  written,  which  was  in  a  pretty  advanced  stage.  My  main
 concern  was  not  to  remain  without the support of the people who possibly
 developed the interface.

 So  the choice not to depend on libraries written by other authors was almost
 mandatory.  Given the mass escape of programmers from this platform, I didn't
 want  to take a risk to write a piece of software based on an interface which
 was supported no more. Had something failed I would have to rewrite the whole
 program or, even worse, to quit developing it.

 Another  thing  I didn't like very much in shareware user interfaces was that
 the  program  would have been only in part a work of mine, and in part a work
 of another person.

 Would I have written half a program???
 Or am I an eccentric people??? :)

 So  I  took the decision to keep on using my own interface. The result is now
 before your eyes.

 At least, if something won't work I will know what went wrong!
@endnode

