@node "GUIResources" "Software Requirements"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}Software Requirements@{ub}@{fg text}

 This graphical user interface uses some functions of the operating system 2.0,
 so  it  won't  work  properly with earlier versions. Resources, and therefore
 functions, of higher operating systems are used if available.

 @{b}Libraries :@{ub}

 exec.library * :)
 intuition.library *
 graphics.library *
 diskfont.library *
 layers.library *
 gadtools.library *
 asl.library *
 utility.library *
 datatypes.library
 locale.library
 amigaguide.library

 @{b}Devices :@{ub}

 console.device
 timer.device
 input.device
 audio.device

 The presence of the marked libraries is mandatory, the other ones are used only
 if available.

@endnode

@node "GUIEditor" "GUI Editor"
@prev "Main"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}GUI Editor@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 The  GUI  configuration window contains some gadgets: they are used to recall
 other   specific  configuration  windows.  This  is  the  list  of  available
 gadgets, together with their function:

 @{"Screens" link "ScreenSettings"}
 Screens preferences, graphical display mode, colors, FONTS selection.

 @{"Windows" link "WindowSettings"}
 Windows   Preferences,   title   color,   border   color,  background  color,
 look.

 @{"Requesters" link "RequesterSettings"}
 Requesters   Preferences,   title  color,  border  color,  background  color,
 look, text frame, waiting time.

 @{"Patterns" link "PatternSettings"}
 Patterns Preferences, selection between pattern 1 or 2, with preview.

 @{"Gruppi" link "GroupSettings"}
 Group gadgets preferences, text color, background color, border type.

 @{"Strings" link "StringSettings"}
 String  gadgets  preference,  text  color, background color, activated-gadget
 text  color,  activated-gadget  background  color,  color of text external to
 gadget, appearance, border type.

 @{"Gadgets" link "GadgetSettings"}
 BUTTON   gadgets   preferences,  text  color,  activated-gadget  text  color,
 background  color,  activated-gadget  background color, XEN gadget background
 color, activated XEN gadget background color, look.

 @{"Texts" link "TextSettings"}
 Text   (or  display)  gadgets  preferences,  text  color,  background  color,
 graphical look, border type.

 @{"Lists" link "ListSettings"}
 List  gadgets preferences, item color, background color, selected item color,
 background item color.

 @{"Borders" link "BorderSettings"}
 Borders  preferences,  border  shine  color, border shadow color, XEN gadgets
 border shadow color, XEN gadgets frame color.

 @{"Misc" link "MiscSettings"}
 Miscellaneous  preferences,  separating  characters  for decimals, thousands,
 dates, lines. Name of temporary files, ASCII viewer selection, choice between
 external/internal ASCII viewer.

 @{"Sounds" link "SoundSettings"}
 Sound  preferences,  selection  of  sounds  for  waits,  positive requesters,
 negative requesters.

 @{"Macro Keys" link "MacroSettings"}
 Function  keys  preferences, NORMAL, SHIFT and ALT set configuration. Loading
 and Saving on external files.

 @{"Load" link "LoadConfig"}
 Allows to load a configuration from file.

 @{"Save" link "SaveConfig"}
 Saves  current  configuration  to  the  file  whose  name is indicated in the
 bottom  display.  If  the  file  exists,  a  confirmation  is required before
 overwriting it.

 @{"Save as" link "SaveasConfig"}
 Saves  current  configuration,  allowing  to  choose the file name via a File
 Requester.

 @{"Default" link "Defaultconfig"}
 Recalls  the default settings of the whole interface. Those settings have the
 same look and behaviour of the standard GadTools.

 @{"Restore" link "RestoreConfig"}
 Restores  all  parameters  to  their previous value, given by the last config
 file loaded.

 @{"Ok" link "OKConfig"}
 Confirms data in memory and quits the editor. Current settings remain active,
 but are not saved to file.

 @{"Cancel" link "AbortConfig"}
 Cancels all modifications and quits the editor.

 @{"File Name" link "FileNameConfig"}
 Constantly displays the name of the last loaded or last saved file.

 N.B.: Some functions can be recalled from the Pull-Down menu as well.

@endnode

@node "ScreenSettings" "Screens Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Screen Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Allows  to  define the screen display mode, to choose among some preset color
 tables, and to select fonts.

 @{b}Clone WB screen@{ub}
 If  active  tells  the  interface to CLONE display mode and dimensions of the
 Workbench screen. This gadget obviously disables the screen mode selection.

 @{b}Screen Mode@{ub}
 Allows  to  select  one  of the graphic display mode contained in the Display
 Database,  using a standard (ASL) requester. Any screen mode up to 256 colors
 (8  bit  deep)  is  supported.  Soon I will release a new version, supporting
 screens up to 24 bits.


 @{b}Color Table@{ub}
 Allows  to  choose  one  among  the  preset  color  palettes,  or  to use the
 Workbench palette.

 @{b}Monospaced Font@{ub}
 Selects a NON proportional font. It will be used wherever it is impossible to
 use  a  proportional  one. You can choose which font and dimension to use via
 standard  (ASL)  font  requester. If the selected font is too big the program
 automatically falls back to Topaz/8.

 @{b}Proportional Font@{ub}
 Selects  the  main font, used for screens, windows and gadgets. All available
 fonts  can  be  used. If the selected font is too big to fit into the screen,
 the interface falls back to Topaz/8.

 @{b}Ok@{ub}
 Accepts all modifications and updates the display if necessary.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Cancels all modifications.

@endnode


@node "WindowSettings" "Windows Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Windows Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}
 Allows  to totally configure the window look. Here are the possible settings:

 @{b}Title Color@{ub}
 Color used to draw window TITLE. It is black by default.

 @{b}Border Color@{ub}
 The color of window borders and titlebar. Default color is light blue.

 @{b}Background Color@{ub}
 The  (background)  color  used to fill the window's interior. Clicking on the
 colored  gadget  a  window defining the color CLASS opens. Now you can choose
 among a plain color, a dithered color or a preset pattern.

 @{b}Graphic look@{ub}
 You  can  change  the  routine which draws the windows. By default the system
 function  is  used,  but if you like more colors you can select one among the
 CUSTOM routines, which draw windows in different ways.

 NOTE:  If  SYSTEM  graphic  look  is selected, title and border color are not
 configurable  and their gadgets appears ghosted. To activate them you have to
 select a different Graphic Look.

 @{b}Test it@{ub}
 Clicking  on  this  button  a test window opens,which is drawn accordingly to
 current  settings. You can thus see the effects of your modifications "on the
 fly".

 @{b}Ok@{ub}
 The  window  is  closed  and all modifications made are accepted. From now on
 any  window   of  the  configuration program will be drawn accordingly to the
 newly defined graphical look.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Cancels all modifications.

@endnode


@node "RequesterSettings" "Requesters Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Requesters Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Customizes  requesters  look.  Configurable  parameters  are  the same of the
 windows, plus some specific others:

 @{b}Title Color@{ub}
 The color used to draw requester TITLE. It is black by default.

 @{b}Border Color@{ub}
 The Color of requester borders and titlebar. Default color is light blue.

 @{b}Background Color@{ub}
 The  color (or pattern) to use to fill the the requester's interior. Clicking
 on  the  colored  gadget a window defining the color CLASS opens. Now you can
 choose among a plain color, a dithered color or a preset pattern.

 @{b}Graphical look@{ub}
 You  can change the routine which draws the requesters. By default the system
 function  is  used,  but if you like more colors you can select one among the
 CUSTOM routines, which draw requesters in different ways.

 NOTE:  If  SYSTEM  graphical look is selected, title and border color are not
 configurable  and  their gadgets appear ghosted. To activate them you have to
 select a different Graphics Look.

 @{b}Rounded Text@{ub}
 If  this  gadget is selected, the text displayed in the requester is enclosed
 in  an  embossed  frame.  If you toggle it off, the text is directly drawn on
 requester's background color (it may result less readable).

 @{b}Timeout@{ub}
 The maximum time the requester should wait before being closed automatically.
 All values between 0 (wait forever) and 99 seconds are allowed. The requester
 normally  opens  with one among its gadgets already selected : if the timeout
 expires, the requester behaves as if you clicked on that gadget, and the same
 happens if you press ENTER.

 @{b}Test it@{ub}
 Clicking  on  this  button  a  test requester opens, it is drawn according to
 current  settings. You can thus see the effects of your modifications "on the
 fly".

 @{b}Ok@{ub}
 The window is closed and any modification accepted. From now on any requester
 will be drawn according to the newly defined graphical look.

 @{b}Annulla@{ub}
 Cancels all modifications.

@endnode

@node "PatternSettings" "Patterns Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Patterns Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This window allows to select one among two patterns by typing its name in its
 respective  string  gadget. The POP-UP gadgets allow an easy selection via an
 ASL File Requester.

 Datatypes  are  used  to  load an image or to remap a palette, so all picture
 formats, whose datatype is present on your system, are supported.

 @{b}
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 If  datatype.library  is  not  found  the patterns preferences gadget will be
 ghosted.
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 @{ub}

 Below the strings gadgets 2 boxes display the previews of the loaded images.

 When  images  with  many colors are loaded, the screen palette is adjusted to
 that  of  the  image:  as  a consequence, any not yet refreshed gadget may be
 displayed using wrong colors. That is fixed automatically by the interface as
 soon as you make the selection and close the window.

 It  is better not to try and load pictures with many colors if the screen you
 have set hasn't enough of them. The result wouldn't be very pleasant anyway.

 Clicking  on  the OK button the selected patterns will be accepted, otherwise
 the  program will reload the previous ones. If none was specified, no pattern
 will be used.

 If  you want to clear the pattern you have to erase the content of the string
 gadgets  and  press  ENTER.  The  two  preview  boxes  will become empty as a
 confirmation.

 The  interface  uses those patterns as two extra "colors" you can use to fill
 any object, such as gadgets, windows, areas and whatever.

@endnode


@node "GroupSettings" "Groups Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Groups Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 These  peculiar  gadgets allow to group together other gadgets. They are kind
 of containers whose name summarizes the function of the gadgets inside them.

 Here are the customizable parameters:

 @{b}Text Color@{ub}
 The  gadget  text  (or  title)  color. Normally the text is printed above the
 gadget itself.

 @{b}Background Color@{ub}
 The  color of the gadget's interior. Any defined pattern can be used as well.
 See also @{"Patterns Preferences" link "PatternSettings"}.

 @{b}Graphical Look@{ub}
 Allows to select the drawing type for this object.

 @{b}Border Type{ub}
 Selects the border drawing mode, normal or inverted.

 @{b}OK@{ub}
 Confirms current settings.

 @{b}Annulla@{ub}
 Restores previous values.

 @{b}Example@{ub}
 Shows the look of the GROUP gadget according to the current settings.

@endnode


@node "StringSettings" "String Gadgets Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}String Gadgets Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  section  allows  to  define  any  of  the  string  gadgets setting. The
 parameters are:

 @{b}Text Color@{ub}
 Text color for non selected gadgets.

 @{b}Background Color@{ub}
 Background color for non selected gadgets.

 @{b}Selected Text Color@{ub}
 Text color while typing (selected gadget).

 @{b}Selected Background@{ub}
 Background color while typing (selected gadget).

 @{b}External Text Color@{ub}
 The color of the text drawn externally to text gadgets.

 @{b}Graphics Look@{ub}
 Chooses the graphical look of the gadget.

 @{b}Border Type@{ub}
 Selects the border drawing mode, normal or inverted.

 @{b}Example of String Gadget@{ub}
 It's  a real-time updated gadget showing the effects of the current settings.
 Clearly,  to  see  the look of the selected gadget you have to activate it by
 pressing ENTER or clicking on it.

 @{b}Ok@{ub}
 Current settings are used.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Restore previous values, modifications are discarded.

@endnode


@node "GadgetSettings" "Gadgets Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Gadgets Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 In  this  section  you  can  define  any setting affecting all gadgets of the
 interface.  These  settings  affect all BUTTON-type gadgets, so the graphical
 appearance  of  all  gadgets  of  this  family  will  be modified. To be more
 precise,  the  same  parameters  (border  and  background  color, text color,
 drawing  type)  will  be  used  for CHECK, POP-UP, CYCLE, SLIDER, ARROW, PROP
 gadgets.

 If  you  activate  the XEN drawing mode, all gadgets of the interface will be
 drawn accordingly to this popular look.

 These are the customizable parameters:

 @{b}Text Color@{ub}
 Text color for non selected gadgets.

 @{b}Selected Text Color@{ub}
 Text color of the gadget when selected (from mouse or keyboard).

 @{b}Background Color@{ub}
 Background color for non selected gadget.

 @{b}Selected Background Color@{ub}
 Background color of the gadget when selected (from mouse or keyboard).

 @{b}Normal Background XEN@{ub}
 Background color for a non selected XEN gadget.

 @{b}Selected Background XEN@{ub}
 Background color for a selected XEN gadget.

 @{b}Graphical Look@{ub}
 Allows  to select the gadgets drawing mode. Two modes are possible: Normal is
 the  classical GadTools-like look while XEN is an advanced drawing mode which
 makes gadgets more pleasant and adds more shades.

 @{b}Test Gadgets@{ub}
 Those  are  two  gadgets  (one  selected  and one plain) which are updated in
 real-time according to the current settings.

 @{b}Ok@{ub}
 Current settings are used.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Restores previous values, modifications are discarded.

@endnode

@node "TextSettings" "Text Gadgets Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Text Gadgets (Display) Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  section  allows to define any of the text gadgets (or display) setting.
 Customizable parameters are:

 @{b}Text Color@{ub}
 Color of the text inside gadgets.

 @{b}Background Color@{ub}
 Background color inside gadgets.

 @{b}Graphical Look@{ub}
 Selects the gadgets drawing mode.

 @{b}Border Type@{ub}
 Selects the border drawing mode, normal or inverted.

 @{b}Current Settings Test@{ub}
 It is a real-time updated gadget reflecting all current graphical settings.

 @{b}Ok@{ub}
 Current settings are used.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Restores previous values, modifications are discarded.

@endnode

@node "ListSettings" "Lists Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Lists Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 In  this  sections you can customize the colors used to display List Gadgets.
 These are the configurable parameters:

 @{b}Item Color@{ub}
 Text color of list entries (items).

 @{b}Background Color@{ub}
 Background color of the area containing entries.

 @{b}Selected Item Color@{ub}
 Background color used to emphasize an entry (item) when it is selected.

 @{b}Sample List@{ub}
 It is a real-time updated gadget reflecting all current graphical settings.

 @{b}Ok@{ub}
 Current settings are used.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Restores previous values, modifications are discarded.

@endnode

@node "BorderSettings" "Borders Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Borders Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 In  this  section you can customize the color used to draw the borders of any
 frame  of  the  GUI.  Normally  these  colors  are  chosen  to  give a three-
 dimensional look to any object.

 @{b}Shine borders@{ub}
 Selects  the  color  of  the  lighted  borders  (light color). It is WHITE by
 default.

 @{b}Shadow borders@{ub}
 Selects  the  color  of  the  shadowed  borders  (dark color). It is BLACK by
 default.

 @{b}XEN shadow borders@{ub}
 Color used to draw the shadowed outline of XEN-type gadgets. It is LIGHT BLUE
 by default.

 @{b}XEN round border@{ub}
 Color used to draw the frame around XEN-type gadgets. It is BLACK by default.

 @{b}Sample@{ub}
 The  window frame below these gadgets contains two rectangular areas, showing
 the current preferences. This helps you in choosing the right colors.

 @{b}Ok@{ub}
 Current settings are used.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Restores previous values, modifications are discaded. 

@endnode


@node "MiscSettings" "Miscellaneous Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Miscellaneous Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  window  allows  to configure some various preferences. Here is what you
 can customize:

 NOTE: the separating characters are simultaneously displayed in two different
 fields:  on  the  left  the  actual character, on the right the corresponding
 ASCII  value.  You can set the character either by typing it directly (on the
 left)  or  by  entering  its  ASCII  value  (on the right). This lets you use
 characters  not  normally accessible via keyboard. Allowed values: from 33 to
 255.

 @{b}Decimal Separator@{ub} and @{b}ASCII decimal@{ub}
 Indicates the character used to display a decimal number.

 @{b}Thousands Separator@{ub} and @{b}ASCII thousands@{ub}
 Indicates the character used to separate thousands in numeric display.

 @{b}Date Separator@{ub} and @{b}ASCII date@{ub}
 Allows  to  set  the  character  used to separate DAY, MONTH and YEAR in date
 display.

 @{b}Lines Character@{ub} and @{b}ASCII lines@{ub}
 It is the character used in reports to draw separating lines.

 @{b}Temporary Filename@{ub}
 It  is  the name programs may use to generate temporary files. Normally it is
 better  to  write  that  file  on the RAM: device, but if you have not enough
 memory  you can indicate a path on your hard disk as well. The file name must
 include the complete path.

 @{b}ASCII Viewer@{ub}
 It  is  the  name  of  the  external  program  you wish to use instead of the
 internal  one  (SDMore).  To  view files you can, for example, use the system
 editor,  or  Multiview.  It is important to specify both program name and any
 parameter  it  may  need to work, ending the line with a %s. The %s tells the
 interface  to  insert  there the file name of the ASCII file to view. You can
 set/edit  this  string  only if the gadget below reads "External (selected)".
 Here is an example configuration using Multiview:

 sys:Utilities/MultiView PUBSCREEN=(screen name) %s

 This one is for CED:

 sys:CED PUBSCREEN=(screen name) %s

 @{b}Default file viewer@{ub}
 The  status  of  this  cycle gadget specifies if the internal (SDMore) or the
 external  (indicated  in  the  above  string) viewer is to be used to display
 ASCII  files.  If external viewer is selected, the "ASCII file viewer" string
 must be correctly set, too.

 @{b}Ok@{ub}
 Current settings are used.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Restores previous values, modifications are discarded.

@endnode


@node "SoundSettings" "Sound Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"

 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Sound (samples) Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 This  window  allows  to  choose  up  to  three  different  sound samples the
 interface can play under particular conditions.

 Every sample is toggled by one among the following events:

 @{b}BUSY wait@{ub}
 It  is  the  sample  the  interface plays whenever an operation requires some
 waiting, or during a presentation (like an information requester).

 @{b}OK Requester@{ub}
 A  sample  played in positive requester, for example after an operation which
 has been correctly performed.
                                      
 @{b}BAD Requester@{ub}
 A  sample played whenever a requester reporting ERRORS or critical situations
 is opened.

 @{b}Test@{ub}
 Every sample can be loop-played by clicking on the corresponding TEST gadget.
 To stop the sample just click on the left mouse button.

 @{b}Ok@{ub}
 Current settings are used.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Restores previous values, modifications are discarded.


 IFF and 8SVX samples are supported.

 If  you  want  no sample associated to a particular condition, just clear the
 contents of the corresponding string gadget.

@endnode

@node "MacroSettings" "Macro Keys Preferences"
@prev "GUIEditor"
 
 @{b}@{u}@{fg shine}Macro Keys Preferences@{ub}@{uu}@{fg text}

 Allows  to  edit  and  customize  the macro assigned to any function key. The
 string  assigned  to  a  function  key can be inserted in any field by simply
 pressing the corresponding function key.

 The  window displays 10 string gadgets: one for each function key. Any string
 can be inserted here.

 There  are  actually  three groups (or banks) of function keys. At the top of
 the  windows  there is a gadget you can use to choose which bank to edit. The
 text  displayed  in that gadget indicates which key combination activates the
 current bank.

 You can also LOAD and SAVE the strings by clicking on the respective gadgets.
 If  you  do  so, please follow the convention of adding a '.tfn' extension to
 the file name.

 Macros  are inserted into their fields only if there is room enough for them.
 They are inserted left to right starting from the current cursor position.

 @{b}Modifier@{ub}
 Selects the function key bank (group). Three banks are available :

 NONE Function key alone. Bank 1

 SHIFT Function key together with SHIFT. Bank 2

 ALT Function key together with ALT. Bank 3

 You  can  recall  a  string  of  the first bank by pressing the corresponding
 function key alone, a string of the second bank by pressing the corresponding
 function key together with the shift key, and so on.

 Thus you can customize up to 30 function keys.

 @{b}F1 ... F2 ... ... F10@{ub}
 The strings corresponding to the function keys.

 @{b}Proceed@{ub}
 Any modification is accepted. Strings are not saved to disk.

 @{b}Load@{ub}
 Allows  you to load a set of function keys strings from a file. The selection
 of the file name is made via an ASL file requester.

 @{b}Save@{ub}
 Allows you to save the current function keys settings to disk. You can select
 the file name via a file requester. All 30 strings are saved.

 @{b}Cancel@{ub}
 Cancels all modifications.

 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 NOTE:  You  can  insert a macro, once defined, into a string gadget either by
 pressing the corresponding function key or by the POP-UP requester that opens
 if you press SHIFT+HELP while the string gadget is active.
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@endnode

@node "LoadConfig" "Load configuration"
@prev "Main"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}Load configuration@{ub}@{fg text}

 Allows  to  load  a  configuration from a file. The selection is made using a
 File  Requester. By default, only files whose name ends in '.prefs' are shown
 in order to make the selection easier.

 Before  loading  the file, its format is checked to avoid any problem. If the
 loading  succeeds  the  interface updates the display, closing the screen and
 the window if necessary.

 The name of the loaded file is shown in the bottom frame (filename).

@endnode

@node "SaveConfig" "Save configuration"
@prev "Main"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}Save configuration@{ub}@{fg text}

 Allows  to  save the current configuration to the file whose name is shown in
 the frame at the bottom. If the file already exists, a requester will ask you
 for confirmation before overwriting it.

 If you wish to save the file with a different name, please select:

 @{"Save as..." link "SaveasConfig"}

@endnode


@node "SaveasConfig" "Save as ..."
@prev "Main"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}Save as ...@{ub}@{fg text}

 Allows  to save the current configuration, selecting the file name via a File
 Requester.  If the selected file already exists, a requester will ask you for
 confirmation before overwriting it.

@endnode

@node "DefaultConfig" "Default"
@prev "Main"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}Default@{ub}@{fg text}

 Restores  the  default settings for the whole interface. The default settings
 give the interface the same look and behaviour as the standard GadTools.

 If any setting was modified, a requester will ask you for confirmation before
 restoring  the  default ones, otherwise the interface will update the display
 according to the preset look.

 Screen mode and fonts are cloned from the Workbench screen.

@endnode

@node "RestoreConfig" "Restore"
@prev "Main"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}Restore@{ub}@{fg text}

 Restores  all  settings  to  the  previous  values, corresponding to the last
 loaded file.

 If any setting was modified, a requester will ask you for confirmation before
 restoring the previous values.

 If  you  proceed,  the  whole display is updated to conform to the last saved
 settings.

@endnode


@node "OkConfig" "Ok"
@prev "Main"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}Ok ... accept configuration@{ub}@{fg text}

 Confirms  the  stored  data  and  quits  the  editor. Current settings remain
 active, but are not saved to disk.

@endnode

@node "AbortConfig" "Cancel"
@prev "Main"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}Cancel@{ub}@{fg text}

 Cancels all modification and quits the editor.

 If any setting was modified, a requester will ask you for confirmation before
 restoring the previous values.

@endnode


@node "FileNameConfig" "File Name"
@prev "Main"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}Nome File@{ub}@{fg text}

 Displays the name of the configuration file stored in memory or last saved to
 disk.

 You  cannot  modify  this  field.  To  select a different file name (to save)
 please use the @{"Save as" link "SaveasConfig"} function.

@endnode



@node "GUIPopUp" "POP-UP Gadgets and Shortcuts"
@prev "Main"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}POP-UP Gadgets and Shortcuts@{ub}@{fg text}

 This  interface provides the user with many so called POP-UP gadgets, because
 they  open  one or more windows which give you full and easy control over any
 kind of setting, let it a number, a color or a file name.

 POP-UP  gadgets  are usually associated to strings or display (text) gadgets.
 They can be activated directly via mouse or using proper key combinations.

 Here are all available POP-UPs:

 @{b}File@{ub}
 Opens an ASL File Requester to select a file.

 @{b}Dir@{ub}
 Opens an ASL File Requester to select a directory.

 @{b}Screen@{ub}
 Opens an ASL Screen Requester to select a screen mode.

 @{b}Font@{ub}
 Opens an ASL Font Requester to select a Font.

 @{b}Macro@{ub}
 Opens a window to directly select a Function Key.

 @{b}Date@{ub}
 Opens a requester which allows to quickly select a date.

 @{b}Month@{ub}
 Opens a requester which allows to quickly select a month or a year.

 @{b}List@{ub}
 Displays a list of selectable items.

 @{b}Value@{ub}
 Opens a requester which allows to quickly select a number.

 @{b}Color@{ub}
 Opens a requester which allows the selection of colors and patterns.

 Every POP-UP gadget has a different image on it.

 The  POP-UP  gadget  can be accessed directly while typing data into a string
 gadget by pressing the combination:

 @{b}@{fg highlight}SHIFT + ARROW DOWN@{ub}@{fg text}

 This activate the POP-UP gadget and opens the associated requester.

 Upon  confirmation  of  the  requester,  the  selected  value  (or string) is
 automatically inserted into the related gadget.

@endnode

@node "GUIShortCuts" "Other key combinations"
@prev "Main"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}Other key combinations@{ub}@{fg text}

 Some gadget, like CYCLE and SLIDER gadgets, can represent more than one value.

 If  you  press  the  key corresponding to one of those gadget (the underlined
 character), the value it represents will be incremented by one. If you do the
 same  while  keeping  the SHIFT key pressed, the value will be decremented by
 one instead.

 The gadgets behaving this way are:

 CYCLES

 COLORS

 PROPS

 SLIDERS

 LISTS

 thus all gadgets which may represent an extended range of values.

 In  PROPS  and  SLIDER gadgets, the related ARROWS increment or decrement the
 value they represent (depending on the arrow direction), and if you keep them
 pressed, their increment or decrement gradually accelerates.

@endnode
 
@node "SDMore" "SDMore ASCII Viewer"
@prev "Main"
 @{b}@{fg highlight}SDMore ASCII Viewer@{ub}@{fg text}

 SDMore  is  just  an  ASCII  file  viewer written to make the reading of long
 reports quick and easy.

 It has the following features :

 - It  can  display  files  of  any length,  provided your computer has enough
   memory.

 - Fast  and  all-directional  scrolling. It is possible to scroll text in all
   four directions.

 - Supports MOUSE and/or keyboard. Both can be used to access any function.

 - Real-time display of the number of text lines, number of the first and last
   line displayed, percentage  of  on-screen text. Another indicator shows the
   offset (in characters) of the working area from the right border.

 - Search  string  function.  You  can  search a string into the whole text by
   typing it into a requester. The search is case sensitive.

 - Gadgets to move to TOP or BOTTOM of the text.

 - Ruler for a correct reading, with no line jumping.

 - The program opens a window that fits the screen.

 - Print function, which offers customization options of type and quality like
   those  in the operative system's "printer" preferences. Checks the presence
   and  status  of  the  printer. Progress bar of printing job with STOP/PAUSE
   gadget. See also @{"Print" link "SDMorePrintFile" 0}


 @{b}@{fg highlight}List of available commands@{ub}@{fg text}

 @{b}HELP@{ub}
 Opens a set of requesters with all available commands.

 @{b}ESC or Quit@{ub}
 Quits SDMore

 @{b}ARROW DOWN@{ub}
 Scrolls the text one line down.

 @{b}SHIFT + ARROW DOWN@{ub}
 Jumps to next page.

 @{b}ARROW UP@{ub}
 Scrolls the text one line up.

 @{b}SHIFT + ARROW UP@{ub}
 Jumps to previous page.

 @{b}ARROW RIGHT@{ub}
 Scrolls the text to the right.
 (if the right margin has not been reached yet)

 @{b}ARROW LEFT@{ub}
 Scrolls the text to the left.
 (if the left margin has not been reached yet)

 @{b}T@{ub}
 Jumps to Top of text.

 @{b}B@{ub}
 Jumps to the last page of text.

 @{b}P@{ub}
 Printer configuration and printing of current file.

 @{b}S@{ub}
 Allows to search a string into the text. The search is case sensitive.

 @{b}R@{ub}
 Toggles ruler On/Off.

 @{b}ALT + ARROW UP@{ub}
 Moves the ruler (if active) one line up.

 @{b}ALT + ARROW DOWN@{ub}
 Moves the ruler (if active) one line down.

 @{b}H@{ub}
 Shows a set of requesters with a summary of available keys.

@endnode

@node "SDMorePrintFile" "SDMore File Print"

 @{b}@{fg highlight}SDMore - Printing files@{ub}@{fg text}

 When you activate the SDMore 'Print' function, the Printer Preferences window
 is  displayed  first.  The  presented  data  are  the same of the Workbench's
 Printer Prefereces program.

 Here are the customizable parameters and their meaning:

 @{b}Driver:@{ub}
 Name  and  version  of  the  currently selected printer driver. To change the
 current  driver  use  Workbench's preferences program and re-select the Print
 function.

 @{b}Left Margin:@{ub}
 This  parameter  affects  the  width  of  the left margin, i.e. the number of
 characters  between  the  sheet's  left  border  and  the  point where actual
 printing  begins.  For  example, if you want a margin of one inch and you are
 using a PITCH of 10, just enter 10 (the pitch is the number of characters per
 horizontal  inch).  (1  inch  =  25.4 mm). The Workbench default is initially
 used, but this value can be modified.

 @{b}Right Margin:@{ub}
 Affects  the width of the right margin, i.e. the number of characters between
 the  sheet's  right  border  and  the  last printable part of every line. For
 example,  if you use a 8,5 inches wide sheet and a pitch of 10 characters per
 inch, then you can print 85 characters per line (8,5 x 10). If you want a one
 inch  wide  right  margin,  then subtract 10 characters: 75 is the number you
 have to type in the 'right margin' field. If the report is 85 characters wide
 and  the  right  margin is 80, the last 5 characters will be printed on a new
 line.  Thus,  to  avoid  unexpected  new  lines just insert a number which is
 higher than the report width.

 @{b}Paper Length:@{ub}
 Represents  the  maximum number of lines per page. It means that every (paper
 length) printed lines a new page header is produced.

 @{b}Paper Size:@{ub}
 This  gadget  allows  to  select  the  size  of the paper used. Values set in
 Workbench preferences are initially used. There are several choices:

 -Custom           (custom paper size, as set in Workbench preferences)

 -US Letter        (8,5 inches wide, 11 tall)
                   (216 x 279 mm.)

 -US Legal         (8,5 inches wide, 14 tall)
                   (216 x 356 mm.)

 -Narrow tractor   (9,5 inches wide, 11 tall)
                   (241 x 279 mm.)

 -Wide tractor     (17,875 inches wide, 11 tall)
                   (454 x 279 mm.)

 Other  settings  for  different  paper formats have not been included because
 they are useless.

 @{b}Print Quality:@{ub}
 This gadget affects the print quality. If you choose DRAFT (fast) the quality
 will  be  low  but the print faster. If you choose Letter (nice) you obtain a
 better quality, but a slower print.

 @{b}Print Pitch:@{ub}
 The  pitch  is  the  number  of  characters  printed  in  1 inch = 25.4 mm of
 horizontal  text; the more the characters, the lesser the space between them.
 Possible options are:

 PICA (10 cpi)      10 characters per inch

 ELITE (12 cpi)     12 characters per inch

 FILE (15 cpi)      15 characters per inch

 @{b}Print spacing:@{ub}
 Print  spacing  affects the number of lines printed in one vertical inch. Two
 options are possible:

 6 lines/inch

 8 lines/inch

 @{b}Auto Form Feed at the end:@{ub}
 If this switch is on, at the end of the printing job a FORM-FEED code is sent
 to  the  printer, causing it to expel the current sheet. If the switch is off
 at the end of the job the printer moves the printing head to the new line and
 waits for the next command.

 @{b}Auto Form Feed every page:@{ub}
 If this switch is on, each time a number of lines equal to the Lines Per Page
 setting are printed, a FORM-FEED (paper advance) code is sent to the printer.
 Doing  so  every  page  of  the report is printed at the beginning of a paper
 sheet.  Otherwise,  if the printer hasn't reached the end of the sheet when a
 report  page  is  finished,  it will start printing the next page in the same
 sheet, thus mangling all next pages of the report.

 @{b}Print:@{ub}
 Starts  printing  the  text  or  report.  Before starting to send data to the
 printer,  a  check  is done whether it is actually present and in its ON-LINE
 status (ready mode). If the printer is not found, a requester warns to set it
 properly.

 This requester remains open until a printer is found.

 Select CANCEL to abort the request.

 @{b}Get from Workbench:@{ub}
 Selecting  this  button  the  program  fetches the informations it needs from
 Workbench preferences, and updates the window accordingly.

 @{b}Cancel:@{ub}
 This gadget aborts the print request.


 During the print job a window shows the printing status. You can stop the job
 by clicking on the STOP gadget. This activates a requester asking if you want
 to resume printing or really stop it.

@endnode
